<subSubSection id="C36E45D0FFAAAC30B091CDCB389090FE" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCB165BFFAAAC30B091CDCB389090FE" blockId="4.[151,1436,249,418]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="B900CA49FFAAAC30B091CDCB3D52904E" bold="true" box="[151,273,249,274]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
♀♂: mid-sized, robust, bees, rarely shorter than 
<quantity id="4C8CBBBEFFAAAC30B33BCDCB3FC1904D" box="[829,898,249,273]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
; bilobed glossa; F 
<number id="3DBC047CFFAAAC30B452CDCB381D904D" box="[1108,1118,249,273]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" value="1.0">1</number>
about as long as F 
<number id="3DBC047CFFAAAC30B531CDCB3905904D" box="[1335,1350,249,273]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" value="2.0">2</number>
; pilose, the hairs longer than flagellum diameter at least on mesosoma; the basal portion of propodeum limited posteriorly by a carina (or sharp change in slope) and divided into pits by longitudinal carinae; fore wing with three submarginal cells; second recurrent vein of hindwing arched outward, “S”-shaped; pterostigma well developed, longer than prestigma; basitibial and pygidial plates and prepygidial and pygidial fimbria absent.
</paragraph>
